Major differences in major championship venues


One of the marks of a major championship is the prestige of the course where it is held. The Masters earns the highest television ratings and is the tournament pros most want to win not because of its field, which is the weakest of the four majors. Its all about Bobby Jones and Augusta National.

A handful of American tournaments travel around the country to different host sites that often make appearances in lists of the top 100 courses: five USGA championships (US Open, US Womens Open, US Amateur, US Womens Amateur, and US Senior Open) and the PGA Championship.

This is a surprisingly short list. The modern-day PGA and LPGA Tours are centered around tournaments which as a group are scattered throughout the country, but individually are contested at the same course every year, or occasionally at different courses in the same geographical area (e.g.FedEx playoff events).

You could even argue that one of the marks of a major tournament is having a rota, which is only possible when an events prestige is strong enough to warrant traveling around the country. The Western Open used to be in the top echelon before decamping to Butler National and later Cog Hill, before folding altogether.

The womens major schedule has been fluid over the past few decades. Of the five current majors, only two of them have been categorized as majors for an extended period of time. The ANA Inspiration, formerly known as the Dinah Shore, has been held at Mission Hills Country Club in Rancho Mirage every year since its creation, while the US Womens Open has traveled the country much like the US Open and the PGA Championship.

The following analysis is based on the joining of two data sets: major host sites and the Golf Digest/Golf Magazine rankings. For each pairing of year and course, we take the highest ranking a course received in one of the two publications within two years of hosting the tournament. For example, Olympic Clubs Lake course hosted the US Open in 2012. In 2011 and 2013, Golf Digest rated it 26th and 27th, respectively, while Golf Digest rated it 25th and 30th. We take the most generous rating and mark down Olympic at 25th for the 2012 US Open.


Overall summary

  • Befitting their stature as the countrys most prominent events - or perhaps indicating that raters disproportionately reward courses for hosting big tournaments - many of these tournaments are played at ranked venues. Large majorities of all four mens events, along with the US Womens Open, held since 1983 have been contested at courses appearing in the Golf Magazine or Golf Digest Top 100 at the time of the tournament.

  • The US Open is in a class by itself, followed by the PGA Championship and US Amateur. Every single US Open since 1983 has been played at a venue ranked in the top 100, and fully half have been played at a course in the top 10. By comparison, a quarter of US Amateurs have been played at top 10 courses and the number is in single digits for all of the other four events.

  • Mens events have traditionally been held at more prestigious courses than womens events. While half or more of PGA Championships and US Amateurs were at courses in the top 30, only a quarter of US Womens Opens have been held at courses in the top 50. Four out of five US Womens Amateurs have been played at courses out of the rankings altogether. For all the talk of growing the womens game, top courses have not stepped up to host the two most prominent USGA events for women. In fact, we will see some evidence later that the situation is getting worse.


Changes over time

  • Examining the median course ranking by decade and tournament largely mirrors the overall results, with a couple important differences. The above charts plot out the ranking of the median course in each decade for the six relevant events. Examining the median, or midpoint, is a good way to approach exploring the typical course in a given era for each event.

  • As before, the US Open is at the top of the heap, followed by the PGA Championship and US Amateur, and going down from there. The median US Open course is ranked a stellar 10th - thats what happens when the most common tournament sites are Pebble Beach (4 times), Shinnecock Hills (4 times), Oakmont (4 times), Pinehurst (3 times), and Olympic (3 times). The US Am and PGA Championship are a little ways back in the 20-30 range.

  • The median ratings of PGA Championship and US Amateur courses took a big jump in the 1990s and have stayed at that level since. In the 1980s, the median PGA course was ranked 54th. Since then, it has been ranked 28th (90s), 25th (00s), and 28th (10s), with similar movement for the US Am. Not too shabby.

  • Most events have seen relative stability in their median course ranking, with the exception of the US Senior Open. When the US Senior Open was inaugurated in the early 1980s, it was held at some of the countrys top courses. Since then, the standing of its host courses has dropped precipitously. More on this later.


Tournaments in detail

  • US Opens are almost exclusively played at the nations most heralded courses. Every single US Open has been played at a ranked course, and the vast majority of events since 1983 have been hosted by a course ranked in the top 30 at the time by Golf Digest or Golf Magazine.

  • There is a clear recent trend of visiting some lower-ranked courses. The USGAs decision to host their flagship event at public venues has resulted in some dots appearing in the lower portion of this chart. Torrey Pines is set to be the least heralded course to host a US Open in the past 30 years, and perhaps ever.

  • Despite this trend, the median course ranking remains largely unchanged. The typical US Open is still held at blue-blood, top-ranked courses. The median ranking by decade is stable: 11th (80s), 10th (90s), 11th (00s), and 9th (10s).

  • Chicken or the egg? Left open is the following question - do US Opens only go to the best courses, or do people think these courses are the best because they hosted the US Open?


  • While top 10 courses are fixtures in the US Open, the typical PGA Championship course is one of the best of the rest. Over the past thirty years, PGA venues have tended to come from the ranks of the nations top courses that arent in the US Open rotation. While the USGA has a lock on blue bloods like Shinnecock and Oakmont, the PGA rotation includes famous but lower-rated courses like Baltusrol, Oakland Hills and Oak Hill. This extends to public courses, as well - the PGA has made repeat visits to the Ocean Course and Whistling Straits, the top public options outside of Bandon, Oregon and USGA stalwarts Pebble Beach and Pinehurst.

  • Unlike the US Open, the PGA does visit unranked and barely-ranked courses. The USGA is hyper-focused on prestige and protecting par. By contrast, the PGA is more flexible about winning scores and also maintains ownership interests that influence (or pollute) its hosting decisions. Bellerive, Atlanta Athletic, and Quail Hollow are large-scale, proven venues in metropolitan areas that may not excite golf architecture enthusiasts but maximize ticket sales and minimize player complaints. Meanwhile, Valhalla is owned by the PGA and Harding Park is administered by the PGA Tours TPC system.

  • The PGA does occasionally nab US Open venues - and may do so more often in the future. Traditionally, when looking at former US Open courses that have moved to hosting PGA Championships, it would have been fair to describe them as courses in which the USGA has lost interest. Olympic changed that. Will more USGA venues follow suit and avoid having the my-way-or-the-highway blue blazer set screw up their courses?

  • Future venues continue the pattern of rotating between mid-ranked traditional hosts and PGA ownership interests, with a bias toward large metro areas:

    • Best of the rest: Ocean Course, Oak Hill
    • USGA outcasts: Olympic, Baltusrol, Congressional, Southern Hills
    • Follow the money: Harding Park, Valhalla, PGA Frisco
    • Big crowds: With the exception of Valhalla and Southern Hills, all of them


  • The US Amateur, still considered by some as a major, has host courses on par with the PGA Championship. By some measures, the US Am is actually played on more prestigious courses than the PGA Championship, with multiple visits to places like Pinehurst, Merion, Oakmont and Pebble Beach since 1983 - places the PGA hasnt visited for decades, if at all.

  • US Am venues, even more so than US Open venues, represent a Whos Who of classic courses. Even the four unranked courses are multiple-time major hosts.


  • The US Senior Open, inaugurated in 1980, started out with a bang but has been on a decline ever since. While traditional US Open venues were popular stops in the first two decades of the US Senior Open, seven of the last eight tournaments were played at unranked courses.

  • Is this the new normal for the over-50 circuit? In the 1980s and 1990s, the stars of the game were chomping at the bit to play on the senior tour and make some extra money. Greg Norman, Nick Faldo, Phil Mickelson and Davis Love, not so much.


  • Mens majors outpace the womens game in course prestige. Only three US Womens Opens since 1983 have been hosted at top 10 venues, while 15 were hosted at unranked ones. When the worlds best female pros visit the Cypress Creek course at Champions Golf Club in Houston this summer, five of the previous six US Womens Opens will have been contested at courses out of the Top 100. This extends to the ANA Inspiration, which is something akin to the LPGAs Masters - Mission Hills may be a nice place, but it is no Augusta National.

  • While golfs leaders have made a lot of noise about helping the womens game, these results suggest that there has been much more talk than action. The median ranking by decade has actually decreased from the 1980s and 1990s (76th and 72nd) to the most recent decades (99th and 97th). American organizers would do well to emulate the R&As work with the Womens British Open. Three courses from the traditional Open Championship rota have been added to the womens rota - the Old Course, Carnoustie, and Royal Liverpool - with Royal Troon following in 2020.

  • Recognition is due to Oakmont and Prairie Dunes for hosting the top female pros. Where are Merion and the Country Club in Brookline? How about Shinnecock Hills or Winged Foot? Medinah, Inverness, and Hazeltine have fallen off the championship rota, why have they not stepped up?


  • The situation is even more dire for the US Womens Amateur. The last time the best female amateurs played the US Womens Am at a ranked course was 2008. They havent played at a top 30 course since 1995.


A final question: whos left?

In total, 118 courses have hosted major tournaments since 1983, 56 of which are currently ranked by one of the two magazines. That leaves 69 ranked courses which are off the tournament rotation. Seven of them are previous professional major hosts:

Course Current High Ranking Number of Pro Majors Most Recent
Chicago 12 3 1911
Garden City 26 1 1902
Winged Foot (East) 41 3 1980
Myopia Hunt 63 4 1908
Aronimink 85 1 1962
Philadelphia Cricket 86 2 1910
Moraine 89 1 1945

Garden City is a mens club and out for good. Myopia Hunt has made it more than 100 years without hosting an event and tops out under 6600 yards so its also probably out. In the interest of fairness and fan interest, Winged Foot would be better off allowing the women and senior men to play on its West course.

The others have actually already made comebacks of varying sorts - Chicago is now back in the limelight having hosted the inaugural US Senior Womens Open, Aronimink is hosting the PGA Championship in a few years and has held FedEx Cup playoff events, and Philadelphia Cricket is hosting this years US Amateur Four-Ball. Moraine is not on the tournament rotation as of yet but in 2016 unveiled a highly lauded renovation that landed it back in the top 100 in Golf Magazines list.

In the meantime, after removing yearly tournament hosts Augusta National and Muirfield Village, we can fantasize about the following list of the top 20 courses that have never hosted the US Open, PGA Championship, or US Womens Open:

If LA Country Club can change its mind, then maybe a golf fan can dream?
